## Coding Rules

* Clean code only
* Readable variable names
* One responsibility per file
* Follow Laravel best practices
* Use Service layer (no fat controller)
* Use validation properly
* Use transactions where needed
* Handle errors properly
* Prefer readability over short code
* Write self-explanatory code (easy to understand without comments)
* Avoid over-complicated one-liners
* Code should be easy to debug and modify
* Refactor unclear code before adding new logic
* Prefer foreach for most logic building
* Use for loop only when index is required
* Avoid while unless necessary

## Development Rules

* Prefer CLI commands
* Show real implementation steps
* Avoid unnecessary packages
* Prefer built-in Laravel features
* Keep performance in mind
* Write scalable solutions
* Prefer single loop solutions
* Avoid nested loops if possible
* Optimize time complexity (O(n) preferred)
* Avoid unnecessary iterations and memory usage
* Use hashing (associative array) for better performance
* Always think performance like large dataset (real production)

## PSR Compact Rules

* Proper naming (camelCase variables, PascalCase classes)
* One class per file
* Keep functions small and single responsibility
* Proper indentation (4 spaces)
* Use meaningful variable names
* Follow consistent formatting
* PHPDoc should contain only method purpose (single line)
* Avoid @param and @return unless required

## Response Rules (VERY IMPORTANT)

* Simple English only
* Short answers
* One task at a time
* No long explanations
* No unnecessary theory
* Give direct solution first
* Then optional explanation (only if needed)
* Always relate to Laravel
* Use real-world examples
* Keep technical words unchanged

* Use Step-by-step ONLY when explanation is required
* Skip steps when user asks:
  - Only questions
  - Only code fix

* For code debugging:
  - Give answer directly in code
  - Use inline `// FIX` comments
  - Do not give explanation before code
  - Make mistakes instantly visible

* If user asks for only questions:
  - Do NOT give Short Answer
  - Do NOT give Steps
  - Directly return list of questions
  - Keep it fast and clean

## Output Format (when applicable)

1. Short Answer
2. Steps
3. Code (if needed)

